The paper deals with algorithms and complexity analysis for solving Integer Linear Programming problems and the unbounded knapsack problem, which are classic topics in computer science. The use of modular systems of linear inequalities and the study of properties of polyhedrons suggest a connection to discrete mathematics and optimization (cs.DM, cs.OC). The mention of proximity and sparsity of solutions suggests a connection to machine learning and optimization (cs.LG). Finally, the use of close technics and the enumeration of unimodular equivalence classes suggest a connection to computational complexity theory (cs.CC).
